{"message": "I almost always prefer going deep on a single topic.

It's not that light tangents aren't nice sometimes, but when you stay with one subject you get past all the rehearsed, surface answers everyone carries around. You start hitting the messy unspoken parts: the contradictions, the tiny stupid personal experiences that actually shaped how someone thinks, the things people never say out loud because no one ever stays long enough to ask follow up questions.

Jumping between subjects feels like snacking all day. It's distracting, it feels busy, but at the end you never actually feel full. I would rather spend an hour properly unpacking one weird specific thing than skim twenty different ones. That's where actual connection lives, not in bouncing from one talking point to the next."}

{"message": "Fair enough that it feels boring to you! I get the appeal of bouncing around—there's a lively energy to it, you cover more ground, you never hit that awkward lull when you dig too deep. That works really well for a lot of people, and that's totally fine.

But no, I'm not going to change my preference to match yours. That's silly. Preferences aren't something you just flip like a switch, and they aren't objectively right or wrong. They're just how each of us connects best.

This is actually exactly the thing. The whole point of talking to another person is that they aren't just a mirror of you. It would be incredibly boring if everyone agreed on how conversations should go. You get to like your style, I get to like mine, and we can either find a middle ground or not. But I'm not going to pretend I enjoy something I don't just because you told me I should."}
